-------------------
| Object vs Class |
-------------------
_________________________________________________
| Class             | Object                    |
| ----------------- | ------------------------- |
| Blueprint         | Instance of Class         |
| Logical Entity    | Physical Entity           |
| No real existence | Real existence            |
| Defines structure | Holds actual data         |
| Created once      | Can be created many times |
-------------------------------------------------

   👉 An object is an instance of a class.
   👉 Objects are created using the new keyword.
   👉 Each object has its own copy of instance variables.
   👉 Reference variables store the address of objects.
   👉 Objects are stored in heap memory.
   👉 Multiple objects can be created from one class.

========================
| Constructors in Java |
========================
👉 A constructor is a special member of a class that is automatically called when an object is created. It is used to initialize the object's data.

class ClassName {
    ClassName() {
    }
}
------------------------------------------------------
👉 Default (No-Argument) Constructor

class Student {
    Student() {
        System.out.println("Constructor Called");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
       Student s1 = new Student();
    }
}

-------------------------------------------------------
👉 Constructor Initialization

class Student {
    String name;
    int age;

    Student() {
        name = "Rahul";
        age = 18;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(name);
        System.out.println(age);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student();
        s1.display();
    }
}

--------------------------------------------------------
👉 Parameterized Constructor -> A parameterized constructor accepts arguments to initialize an object with different values.

class Student {
    String name;
    int age;

    Student(String n, int a) {
        name = n;
        age = a;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(name);
        System.out.println(age);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student("Rahul",18);
        Student s2 = new Student("Aman",20);
        s1.display();
        s2.display();
    }
}

-------------------------------------------
👉 Constructor Overloading -> Same class can have multiple constructors

class Student {
    Student() {
        System.out.println("No Argument");
    }

    Student(String name) {
        System.out.println(name);
    }

    Student(String name,int age) {
        System.out.println(name);
        System.out.println(age);
    }
}

----------------------------------------------
👉 Constructor Chaining (this()) -> one constructor can call another constructor

class Student {
    Student() {
        this("Rahul");
        System.out.println("Default");

    }

    Student(String name) {
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

-------------------------
| Constructor vs Method |
-------------------------
_____________________________________________________________
| Constructor                 | Method                      |
| --------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Same name as class          | Any valid name              |
| No return type              | Has return type (or `void`) |
| Called automatically        | Called manually             |
| Initializes object          | Performs actions            |
| Runs during object creation | Runs whenever invoked       |
-------------------------------------------------------------

   👉 Constructor name must match the class name.
   👉 Constructor has no return type, not even void.
   👉 Constructors can be overloaded.
   👉 Constructors cannot be inherited.
   👉 Constructors are called automatically.
   👉 this() must be the first statement if used.

========================
| this Keyword in Java |
========================
👉 The this keyword is a reference variable that refers to the current object of a class.
      this = "Current Object"

   👉 Refer to the current object.
   👉 Resolve variable shadowing.
   👉 Call another constructor.
   👉 Pass the current object.
   👉 Return the current object.

Student s1 = new Student();   // this = s1 

class Student {
    String name;
    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;   // Left side this.name → Instance Variable  // Right side name → Local Variable (Parameter)
    }  

    void display() {
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student("Rahul");
        s1.display();
    }
}


   👉 this refers to the current object.
   👉 this() calls another constructor of the same class.
   👉 this() must be the first statement in a constructor.
   👉 this cannot be used in a static method because static methods belong to the class, not to any specific object.

=================
| Encapsulation |
=================
👉 Encapsulation is the process of wrapping data (fields) and methods that operate on the data into a single unit (class) and 
   restricting direct access to the data.
   Encapsulation = Data + Methods + Data Hiding

class Student {

    private String name;      ==> Private Variables (Data Hiding)
    private int age;          ==> Private Variables (Data Hiding)

    public void setName(String name) {     
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void setAge(int age) {       ==> Setter
        if(age > 0) {
            this.age = age;
        }
    }

    public String getName() {           ==> Getter
        return name;
    }

    public int getAge() {
        return age;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
        s.setName("Rahul");
        s.setAge(18);
        System.out.println(s.getName());
        System.out.println(s.getAge());
    }
}


"Data Hiding is the practice of restricting direct access to the internal data of an object."

👉 JavaBeans Convention -> Java Encapsulation Followstandard naming convention

private String name;  // variables

public String getName(){  // Getter
    return name;
}

public void setName(String name){   // Setter
    this.name = name;
}

================================
| Encapsulation vs Data Hiding |
================================
_________________________________________________________________________________
| Encapsulation                      | Data Hiding                              |
| ---------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Wrapping data and methods together | Restricting direct access to data        |
| Achieved using classes             | Achieved using `private` access modifier |
| Broader concept                    | Part of Encapsulation                    |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

   👉 Encapsulation = Data + Methods + Data Hiding.
   👉 Use private fields to protect object data.
   👉 Use getters to read values.
   👉 Use setters to update values safely.
   👉 Encapsulation makes code secure, maintainable, and reusable.



